    <!-- ═══ CHOOSING A MANUFACTURER ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="choosing-heading">
      <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Selection Guide</div>
        <h2 id="choosing-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-10">
          How to <span class="text-accent">Choose</span> a Conveyor Manufacturer
        </h2>

        <div class="max-w-4xl space-y-8">
          <div>
            <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mb-4">Start With Your Application, Not the Manufacturer</h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
              Define your requirements before contacting vendors: product dimensions and weight, throughput rate, environment (ambient, washdown, cleanroom, outdoor), regulatory requirements (FDA, USDA, ATEX, Class 100), and integration points with upstream and downstream equipment. A clear specification reduces quote variance and helps you compare vendors on equal terms. See our <a href="/resources/conveyor-cost-guide/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">cost guide</a> for factors that drive pricing.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mb-4">Evaluate Industry Experience</h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
              A manufacturer that has built 200 <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/bakery/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">bakery conveyors</a> will anticipate problems , flour dust ingress, high-temperature exposure, sanitation protocols , that a general-purpose builder may not. Ask for case studies or references in your specific industry. If the manufacturer cannot provide them, that does not disqualify them, but it means you should scrutinize their design more carefully.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mb-4">Consider Total Cost of Ownership</h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
              The purchase price is one component of conveyor cost. Long-term costs include energy consumption, <a href="/resources/conveyor-parts/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">replacement parts</a> (belts, rollers, bearings, motors), maintenance labor, and downtime. A conveyor with standard catalog parts from multiple suppliers will cost less to maintain than one with proprietary components available only from the OEM. Ask manufacturers what percentage of wear parts are standard versus proprietary.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mb-4">Geographic Proximity Matters</h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
              For installation support, emergency service, and parts delivery, proximity reduces response time and travel costs. This does not mean you must buy local , many manufacturers service nationally , but a company with a service center within a few hours of your facility can respond to breakdowns faster. See our <a href="/resources/conveyor-companies/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor companies near you</a> guide for regional search strategies.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mb-4">Get Multiple Quotes</h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
              Request quotes from at least 2&ndash;3 manufacturers. Ensure all vendors are quoting on the same specification , same conveyor type, length, width, speed, load capacity, material of construction, controls scope, and installation scope. Price differences of 20&ndash;40% between qualified vendors are common and reflect differences in manufacturing approach, overhead structure, and local market conditions, not necessarily quality differences.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

